Wash and dry produce.

Trim and thinly slice @scallions{2}, separating whites from greens. Trim @green beans{6%oz} if necessary.

Melt @butter{1%tbsp} in a #medium pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Israeli couscous{3/4%cup}, scallion whites, and @Italian seasoning{1/2%tsp}; cook, stirring occasionally, until lightly toasted, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Add @water{1%cup}, @chicken stock concentrate{1}, and a @salt{pinch}. Bring to a boil, then cover and reduce to heat to low. Cook until couscous is al dente, ~{6-8%minutes}.

Drain any excess liquid if necessary. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

While couscous cooks, heat a drizzle of @cooking oil{} in a #large nonstick pan{} over medium-high heat. Add green beans and a pinch of @salt{pinch}; cook, stirring constantly, until evenly coated in oil, ~{30%seconds}.

Carefully add @water{1/4%cup} and cover with a #lid{}. Cook, shaking the pan occasionally, until green beans begin to soften and turn bright green, ~{1-3%minutes}.

Once liquid has absorbed, turn off heat. Taste and season with additional @salt{} or @pepper{} if desired; stir to combine.

Pat @salmon{10%oz} dry with #paper towels{}. Season all over with remaining @Italian seasoning{1/2%tbsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{} in pan used for green beans over medium-high heat. Add salmon, skin sides down, and cook until skin is crispy, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Flip and cook until fish is opaque and cooked through, ~{1-2%minutes} more. Remove from pan and set aside.

While salmon cooks, zest and quarter @lemon{1}. Quarter @grape tomatoes{4%oz}.

In a #small bowl{}, combine @crema{1.5%tbsp}, @lemon zest{1/4%tsp}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}; stir in scallion greens, green beans, tomatoes, remaining lemon zest, and a squeeze of lemon juice. Season with salt and pepper.

Divide couscous between #bowls{} or #plates{}; top with salmon. Drizzle everything with zesty crema. Serve with remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Fish is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.